Global Pandemic Analysis¶

Introduction¶

A pandemic is defined as an epidemic of an infectious disease that has spread across a large region such as multiple continents or worldwide, affecting a substantial number of individuals. Throughout human history, there have been a number of pandemics with the most fatal being the Black Death (also known as The Plague), which killed an estimated 75–200 million people in the 14th century [1]. Recent pandemics include tuberculosis, Russian flu, Spanish flu, Asian flu, cholera, Hong Kong flu, HIV/AIDS, Swine flu and COVID-19.

This report provides visualisation of the current COVID-19 pandemic (attributed to the SARS-CoV-2 Coronavirus) and the relationship between different data with some comparison to Swine flu.

Data used in this analysis¶

This analysis uses data from two different sources.

The main dataset used is named: “The complete Our World in Data COVID-19 dataset”. This data set is available in CSV format and can be downloaded from: https://covid.ourworldindata.org/data/owid-covid-data.csv

The file name for this dataset is 'owid-covid-data.csv' and has 153394 rows and 63 properties for each row. The data contains daily statistics from 22nd January 2020 to the present day.

The second dataset used in this analysis is named: "H1N1 | 2009 | Swine Flu Pandemic". This data set is available in CSV format and can be downloaded from: https://www.kaggle.com/imdevskp/h1n1-swine-flu-2009-pandemic-dataset

The file name for this data set is 'data.csv' and has 2489 Rows across 5 columns. The CSV file contains day by day country wise number of cases & deaths of Swine flu from 4th April to 6th July 2009. With respect to data for Australia, this data set spans from 9th May to 6th July, 2009, a total of 58 days.

Each row represents a unique observation set and each observation set contains the attributes shown in the table below:

Variable Description Type
Date Date of observation. Date
Country Country or region. String
Cumulative no. of cases Cumulative number of cases. Integer
Cumulative np. of deaths Cumulative number of deaths. Integer
Link Link to the data source. String

Visualisations¶

1. How do the cumulative number of cases between H1N1 (Swine Flu) and COVID-19 compare during the first 8 weeks after the first cases were detected in Australia?¶

In 2009, a new H1N1 influenza virus emerged, causing the first global flu pandemic in 40 years. On April 15th, 2009 the first human infection with new influenza A (H1N1) virus was detected in California, U.S.A. This virus took 24 days to reach Australia. Just over ten years later, the first reported case of COVID-19 was reported in Wuhan, China on 31st December 2019. This virus took 25 days to reach Australia [2].

The fact that both viruses took a similar amount of time to reach Australian shores is interesting and this forms the motivation to compare the rate of spread between the two pandemics during the crucial first two months from the first detection date in Australia.

In the following Area Plot we compare the number of cumulative deaths in Australia over the first 8 weeks for each pandemic. The data in this graph comes from the two different data sets:

In [3]:
# Ensuring the plot is displayed directly below the code cell that produced it:

%matplotlib inline

# importing libraries:

import pandas as pd                           # importing pandas library with structures and operations to manipulate data.

import numpy as np                            # manipulation of arrays.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt               # importing matplotlib.pyplot for setting style and plot attributes.

import seaborn as sns                         # importing seaborn for statistical data visualisation.

sns.set()                                     # set seaborn style

# using Pandas to read in 1st csv file as 'covid_df', filtering raw data with required columns and parsing dates:

covid_df = pd.read_csv('owid-covid-data.csv', usecols=["date","location","total_cases"], parse_dates=['date'])

# using Pandas to read in 2nd csv file as 'swine_flu_df', filtering raw data with required columns and parsing dates:

swine_flu_df = pd.read_csv('data.csv', usecols=["Date","Country","Cumulative no. of cases"], parse_dates=['Date'])

# filtering the attribute 'location' so that 'covid_df' data frame only contains rows containing 'Australia'.

covid_df = covid_df.query('location == "Australia"') 

# filtering the attribute 'Country' so that 'swine_flu_df' data frame only contains rows containing 'Australia'.

swine_flu_df = swine_flu_df.query("Country == 'Australia'")

# upon inspection we note that 'swine_flu_df' has 23 missing dates in the first 8 weeks of data.
# the dates in 'swine_flu_df' are NumPy 'datetime64' type which encodes the dates as 64-bit integers.

# converting to Pandas Date time object and setting format (this is to setup for the resample):

swine_flu_df['Date'] =  pd.to_datetime(swine_flu_df['Date'], format='%Y/%m/%d') 

# setting the index of the df to Date:

swine_flu_df.set_index('Date', inplace=True) 

# Adding missing dates and interpolates mean value from neighbouring rows. However it also creates NaN's for 'Country':

swine_flu_df= swine_flu_df.resample('D').interpolate().reset_index() 

# The data frame now has NaNs in place of the country name where values have been imputed.

# This fills the NaN's with the most frequent value from the column 'Country':

swine_flu_df = swine_flu_df.fillna(swine_flu_df['Country'].value_counts().index[0]) 

# we now have consecutive days with interpolated case number values for the first 58 days that swine flu was in Australia
# (keeping in mind that the data in this set spans 58 days).

# Resetting the index of 'covid_df':

covid_df = covid_df.reset_index() 

# Selecting the first 56 rows of 'covid_df':

covid_df = covid_df[:56]

# selecting the first 56 rows of 'swine_flu_df':

swine_flu_df = swine_flu_df[:56]

# we now have two data frames with the same number of rows.
# concatenating both data frames across axis 1:

joined_df = pd.concat([covid_df, swine_flu_df], axis = 1)

# renaming the existing data frames columns:

joined_df.rename(columns={'total_cases': 'COVID-19 Cases', 'Cumulative no. of cases': 'Swine Flu Cases'}, inplace=True) 

# At this stage we now have corresponding values for the first 56 days of each pandemic in Australia.
# we can therefore remove locations and dates so that we are left with corresponding raw values for number of cases
# for each respective pandemic in ascending order:

# Select sub set of columns and assigning value to 'final_df':

final_df = (joined_df[['COVID-19 Cases','Swine Flu Cases']])

# Now we can plot:

# defining range for x:

x = range(1,57)

# defining data for y:

cases = [final_df['COVID-19 Cases'],final_df['Swine Flu Cases']]

plt.figure(figsize=(13,5))        # setting figure size.

# setting the tick values for the x-axis:

plt.xticks(np.arange(0,58, 4.0)) 

# Basic stacked area chart with labels and chosen colours:

plt.stackplot(x,cases, labels=['COVID-19 Cases','Swine Flu Cases'], colors = ['tomato', 'lightsalmon'], alpha = 0.7)

plt.legend(loc='upper left')      # setting legend with positioning.

plt.xlabel('Days into Pandemic')  # setting x-axis label.

plt.ylabel('Number of Cases')     # setting y-axis label.

plt.title('Number of Cases in Australia for the First 8 weeks of Each Pandemic')  # setting title of graph.

plt.show()                        # show the graph.

From the Area Plot we can see that the number of Swine Flu cases grew more rapidly compared to COVID-19 case numbers. After 8 weeks there were approximately five and a half times more Swine Flu cases.

2. How do the total deaths between H1N1 (Swine Flu) and COVID-19 compare during the first 8 weeks after the first cases were detected in Australia?¶

Now we look at deaths in Australia for the same period of time. As before, this plot uses data from two different data sets:

%matplotlib inline

import pandas as pd                           # importing pandas library with structures and operations to manipulate data.

sns.set()                                     # set seaborn style


# using Pandas to read in 1st csv file as 'covid_df', filtering data with required columns and parsing dates:

covid_df = pd.read_csv('owid-covid-data.csv', usecols=["date", "location", "total_deaths"], parse_dates=['date']) 

# using Pandas to read in 2nd csv file as 'swine_flu_df', filtering raw data with required columns and parsing dates:

swine_flu_df = pd.read_csv('data.csv', usecols=["Date", "Country", "Cumulative no. of deaths"], parse_dates=['Date'])

# filtering attribute 'location' so that 'covid_df' data frame only contains rows containing 'Australia':

covid_df = covid_df.query('location == "Australia"')

# filtering attribute 'Country' so that 'swine_flu_df' data frame only contains rows containing 'Australia':

swine_flu_df = swine_flu_df.query("Country == 'Australia'")

# Upon inspection we note that swine_flu_df has 23 missing dates in the first two months of data.
# The dates are in NumPy 'datetime64' type which encodes the dates as 64-bit integers.

# Coverting to Pandas Date time object and setting format (this is to set up for resample):

swine_flu_df['Date'] =  pd.to_datetime(swine_flu_df['Date'], format='%Y/%m/%d') 

# Setting the index of the df to Date:

swine_flu_df.set_index('Date', inplace=True)

# Adding missing dates and interpolates mean value from neighbouring rows. However this also creates NaN's for 'Country':

swine_flu_df= swine_flu_df.resample('D').interpolate().reset_index() 

# This fills the NaN's with the most frequent value from the column 'Country':

swine_flu_df = swine_flu_df.fillna(swine_flu_df['Country'].value_counts().index[0]) 

# we now have consecutive days with interpolated death number values for the first 58 days that swine flu was in Australia.

# Resetting the index to 'covid_df':

covid_df = covid_df.reset_index() 

# Selecting the first 56 rows:

covid_df = covid_df[:56]

# selecting the first 56 rows of 'swine_flu-df':

swine_flu_df = swine_flu_df[:56]

# Concatenating both data frames across axis 1:

joined_df = pd.concat([covid_df, swine_flu_df], axis = 1) 

# Renaming the existing data frames columns:

joined_df.rename(columns={'total_deaths': 'COVID-19 Deaths', 'Cumulative no. of deaths': 'Swine Flu Deaths'}, inplace=True) 

# At this stage we now have corresponding values for the first 56 days of each pandemic in Australia.
# we can therefore remove locations and dates so that we are left with corresponding raw values for number of cases
# for each respective pandemic in ascending order:

# Selecting required subset of columns:

final_df = (joined_df[['COVID-19 Deaths','Swine Flu Deaths']]) 

# Now we can plot:

# Defining range for x:

xx = range(1,57)

# Defining data for y:

deaths = [final_df['COVID-19 Deaths'],final_df['Swine Flu Deaths']]

plt.figure(figsize=(13,5))        # setting figure size.

# Setting the tick values to represent whole numbers (instead half numbers since values were interpolated):

plt.yticks(np.arange(1,18, 2.0)) 

# setting the tick values for the x-axis:

plt.xticks(np.arange(36,58, 2.0)) 

# Basic stacked area chart with baseline set to zero and with chosen colours:

plt.stackplot(xx, deaths, labels = ['COVID-19 Deaths','Swine Flu Deaths'], baseline = 'zero', 
              colors = ['tomato', 'lightsalmon'],alpha = 0.7)

plt.legend(loc='upper left')       # setting legend with positioning.

plt.xlabel('Days into Pandemic')   # setting x-axis label.

plt.ylabel('Number of Deaths')     # setting y-axis label.

plt.title('Number of Deaths in Australia for the First 2 Months of Pandemics')  # Title of Graph:

plt.show()                         # plot graph.

Despite there being a larger number of overall deaths of Swine Flu compared to COVID-19 during the first 8 weeks in Australia, the number of COVID-19 deaths per case was greater than the number of Swine Flu deaths per case. Given this fact, it could be argued that a greater level of media attention to COVID-19 produced a heightened public awareness which may have had a limiting effect on death numbers as more people paid attention to mechanisms which avoided the spreading of the virus.

3. Is there a noticeable difference in COVID death rates between Countries?¶

This graph shows the change in death rate over time for Russia, Germany, Australia, United States, and New Zealand. The death rate was calculated by taking the quotient between the 'total number of deaths per million' and the 'total number of COVID-19 cases per million' for each respective country and thus creating a new variable 'death_rate'. The resultant output is a time series line plot with unique trajectories of death rate for each country.

In [5]:
# Ensuring the plot is displayed directly below the code cell that produced it:

%matplotlib inline

# libraries:

import pandas as pd                           # importing pandas library with structures and operations to manipulate data.

import numpy as np                            # manipulation of arrays. 

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt               # importing matplotlib.pyplot for setting style and plot attributes.

import matplotlib.dates as mdates             # importing matplotlib.mdates for manipulation of date formatting.

import seaborn as sns                         # importing seaborn for statistical data visualisation.


sns.set(font_scale = 1.5, rc={"lines.linewidth": 2.0}, style = "whitegrid")  # Use white grid plot background from seaborn.

plt.figure(figsize = (15, 8))                     # setting figure size.

df_dict = {}                                      # defining empty dictionary 'df_dict'.

# importing csv as Pandas dataframe, filtering raw data with required columns and parsing dates:

dframe = pd.read_csv('owid-covid-data.csv', usecols=['date','location', 
                    'total_deaths_per_million', 'total_cases_per_million'], parse_dates=['date'])   


df_dict['filtered_df1'] = dframe.query('location == "Russia"')          # filtering attribute 'location' so that the key
                                                                        # 'filtered_df1' in 'df_dict' only contains values
                                                                        # for 'Russia'.
                                                                      
df_dict['filtered_df2'] = dframe.query('location == "Australia"')       # filtering attribute 'location' so that the key 
                                                                        # 'filtered_df2' in 'df_dict' only contains values
                                                                        # for 'Australia'.

df_dict['filtered_df3'] = dframe.query('location == "Germany"')         # filtering attribute 'location' so that the key
                                                                        # 'filtered_df3' in 'df_dict' only contains values
                                                                        # for 'Germany'.


df_dict['filtered_df4'] = dframe.query('location == "United States"')   # filtering attribute 'location' so that the key
                                                                        # 'filtered_df4' in 'df_dict' only contains values
                                                                        # for 'United States'. 


df_dict['filtered_df5'] = dframe.query('location == "New Zealand"')     # filtering attribute 'location' so that the key 
                                                                        # 'filtered_df5' in 'df_dict' only contains values
                                                                        # for 'New Zealand'.

        
tdpm_dict = {}                                                          # defining empty dictionary 'tdpm_dict'.

tdpm_dict["tdpm"] = np.array([dframe.total_deaths_per_million])         # creating an array of the variable 
                                                                        # 'total deaths per million'.
    
tcpm_dict = {}                                                          # defining empty dictionary 'tcpm_dict'.

tcpm_dict["tcpm"] = np.array([dframe.total_cases_per_million])          # creating an array of the variable 
                                                                        # 'total cases per million'.

dr_dict = {}                                                            # defining empty dictionary 'dr_dict'.
                
dr_dict["death_rate"] = np.divide(tdpm_dict["tdpm"],tcpm_dict["tcpm"])  # taking the quotient of the 
                                                                        # two variables to create the key
                                                                        # 'death rate' in 'dr_dict'.

        
dr_df_dict = {}                                                         # defining empty dictionary 'dr_df_dict'.

dr_df_dict["death_rate"] = pd.DataFrame(dr_dict["death_rate"])          # converting 'death rate'
                                                                        # array to data frame.

dr_df_trans_dict = {}                                                   # defining empty dictionary 'dr_df_tdict'.

dr_df_trans_dict["death_rate"] = dr_df_dict["death_rate"].transpose()   # transposing 'death rate'
                                                                        # data frame to make concatenation 
                                                                        # possible.
    
dr_df_trans_dict["death_rate"].reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)     # reset indexes to enable proper 
                                                                        # concatenation for RHS data frame.
        
dframe.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)                             # reset indices to enable proper 
                                                                        # concatenation for LHS data frame.

    
df_final_dict = {}                                                      # defining empty dictionary 'df_final_dict'.  



for i in range(1,6):                                                    # creating a for loop.

   

    # select subset of columns for specific countries prior to concatenation:
    
    df_final_dict ["df%s"%i] = (df_dict["filtered_df%s" %i][['location', 'date']])     
                                                                                 
    # concatenating two data frames into one:
    
    df_final_dict ["df%s"%i] = pd.concat([df_final_dict["df%s"%i], dr_df_trans_dict["death_rate"]], 
                                   axis=1, ignore_index = True)                               
                                                                                             
    # rename column with relevant title:
    
    df_final_dict ["df%s"%i].rename(columns = {1:'Date'}, inplace = True)  
    
    # rename column with relevant title:
    
    df_final_dict ["df%s"%i].rename(columns = {0:'Location'}, inplace = True) 
    
    # rename column with relevant title:
    
    df_final_dict ["df%s"%i].rename(columns = {2:'Death Rate'}, inplace = True)         
    
# Now we can set the parameters for the plot.
    
# gca() function used to get the current axes:

ax = plt.gca()                                                                           
                                                                                        
ax.set_title("Time Series Comparison of COVID-19 Death Rates Between Five Countries")   # plot title.

ax.set_xlabel("Date")                                                                   # x-axis label.

ax.set_ylabel("Death Rate [death/cases]")                                               # y-axis label.


# plot Russian specific data in blue:

df_final_dict ["df1"].plot(kind='line', x='Date',y='Death Rate', label = 'Russia', color = 'blue', ax=ax)         
                                                                                                             
# plot Australian specific data in red:                                                                                                             
        
df_final_dict ["df2"].plot(kind='line', x='Date', y='Death Rate', label = 'Australia', color = 'red', ax=ax) 

# plot German specific data in purple:    
           
df_final_dict ["df3"].plot(kind='line', x='Date', y='Death Rate', label = 'Germany', color = 'purple', ax=ax) 

# plot United States specific data in green:

df_final_dict ["df4"].plot(kind='line', x='Date', y='Death Rate', label = 'United States', color = 'green', ax=ax) 

# plot New Zealand specific data in orange:
                       
df_final_dict ["df5"].plot(kind='line', x='Date', y='Death Rate', label = 'New Zealand', color = 'orange', ax=ax) 



date_form = mdates.DateFormatter("%b-%y")      # format dates to display three letters of month then year.

ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(date_form)        # specify the format of major ticks on x-axis.

four_mths = mdates.MonthLocator(interval=4)    # specify intervals between major ticks to four months.

ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(four_mths)          # set major x-axis ticks.

plt.xticks(rotation=0)                         # no rotation on x-axis labels

plt.show()                                     # show plot.

5. Is there a relationship between the median age of a population and the average reproduction rate of the SARS-CoV-2 Coronavirus?¶

Here we look at global data and compare all non-zero values for mean Coronavirus reproduction rates per country and plot against the respective median age of that country. The data points are then coloured by life expectancy to add an extra dimension to the plot. Average reproduction rates per location were computed through the use of the group_by() and mean() functions:

In [7]:
# Ensuring the plot is displayed directly below the code cell that produced it:

%matplotlib inline

# libraries:

import pandas as pd                            # importing pandas library with structures and operations to manipulate data.

import numpy as np                             # import NumPy to assist with manipulation of data frames. 

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt                # setting style and plot attributes such as the range for x and y axes

import seaborn as sns                          # importing seaborn for statistical data visualisation.

sns.set(font_scale = 1.2, style = "darkgrid")  # use dark grid plot background from seaborn.

# importing csv as Pandas dataframe, filtering raw data with required columns and parsing dates:

dframe = pd.read_csv('owid-covid-data.csv', usecols=['date','location','population', 'life_expectancy', 
                            'reproduction_rate', 'median_age'], parse_dates=['date'])    
  
grouped_df = dframe.groupby('location')        # grouping data frame by 'location' and assigning to variable 'grouped_df'.
                                                
mean = grouped_df.mean()                       # using the mean() function and assigning values to 'mean'.

mean = mean.replace(0, np.nan)                 # replacing zeros with NaN.

mean = mean.dropna()                           # drop all rows with NaN.

mean = mean.reset_index()                      # resetting the index.

plt.figure(figsize=(15,8))                     # specify size of plot.
    

    
ax = sns.scatterplot(data=mean, x= "median_age", y="reproduction_rate",
                     hue = 'life_expectancy',s = 70, palette = 'flare_r')   # Specify scatterplot with parameters.
    
ax = plt.gca()                                                              # gca() function used to get current axis.

ax.set_title("Median Age Versus Average Reproduction Rate of Coronavirus Per Country")  # set title of plot.

ax.set_xlabel("Median Age")                                                 # set x-axis label for plot.

ax.set_ylabel("Average Reproduction Rate of Virus")                         # set y-axis label for plot.

ax.get_legend().set_title("Life Expectancy")                                # set label for legend.

plt.show()                                                                  # show plot.

From the scatterplot we can see that the majority of the data points for the average reproduction rate of the virus tend to converge to values between 1 and 1.2. We can also see that the median age of a country is closely linked to its life expectancy.

# libraries:

import pandas as pd                           # importing pandas library with structures and operations to manipulate data.

import numpy as np                            # manipulation of arrays.

import seaborn as sns                         # importing seaborn for statistical data visualisation.

# importing data as a panda data frame, filtering raw data with required columns and parsing dates:

dframe = pd.read_csv('owid-covid-data.csv', usecols=['location','date', 'new_cases'], parse_dates=['date'])

# Splitting dates to create two new columns in the data frame:

dframe['year'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(dframe['date']).year           # creating a column for 'year'.

dframe['month'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(dframe['date']).month         # creating a column for 'month'.

dframe = dframe.set_index('date')                                # setting index to 'date'.

# using a query to create sub sets of 'dframe' where each sub set data frame only holds values for a specific location:

rus_df = dframe.query('location == "Russia"')
aus_df = dframe.query('location == "Australia"')

usa_df = dframe.query('location == "United States"')
new_df = dframe.query('location == "New Zealand"')
sou_df = dframe.query('location == "South Africa"')
can_df = dframe.query('location == "Canada"')
jap_df = dframe.query('location == "Japan"')
afr_df = dframe.query('location == "Africa"')
bra_df = dframe.query('location == "Brazil"')

# Now we process the required data for each Country. We start with Russia:

rus_df21 = rus_df['2021-02-01' :'2021-12-31']                                                   # specifying date range for
                                                                                                # eleven months in 2021 and 
                                                                                                # assigning to 'rus_df21'.
    
rus_new_cases21 = rus_df21.groupby('month').agg(qty =('new_cases', 'sum')).astype({'qty':int})  # grouping data by 'month'
                                                                                                # and summing values of 
                                                                                                # 'new_cases', then assigning
                                                                                                # to 'rus_new_cases21'.

                                                                                                # one month in 2022 and 
                                                                                                # assigning to 'rus_df22'.

                                                                                                # and summing values of 
                                                                                                # 'new_cases', then assigning
                                                                                                # to 'rus_new_cases22'.

                                                                                                # 'rus_new_cases21' with
                                                                                                # 'rus_new_cases22' and 
                                                                                                # assigning to 'rus_data'
                                                                                                # so that data for Jan 2022 
                                                                                                # comes after 2021 data.
                                                                                                
                        
rus_data = rus_data.rename(columns = {'qty':'Russia'})                                          # renaming the 'qty' column
                                                                                                # to name of the Country.

    
# This whole process is repeated for each respective country

aus_df21 = aus_df['2021-02-01' :'2021-12-31']

final_df = pd.concat([rus_data, aus_data, ger_data, usa_data, new_data, sou_data, 
                      can_data, jap_data, afr_data, bra_data], axis = 1)

final_df.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)              # resetting the index.

final_df = final_df.transpose()                            # transposing the data frame.

plt.title('COVID-19 Cases Per Month (February 2021 to January 2022)')  # specify title of plot.

                 cmap="BuPu",robust = True, linewidth = 0.5, center = 420000)

plt.show()                                                 # show plot.

jap_new_cases22 = jap_df22.groupby('month').agg(qty =('new_cases_per_million', 'sum')).astype({'qty':int})

jap_data = jap_data.rename(columns = {'qty':'Japan'})

# Africa:

afr_df21 = afr_df['2021-02-01' :'2021-12-31']
afr_new_cases21 = afr_df21.groupby('month').agg(qty =('new_cases_per_million', 'sum')).astype({'qty':int})
afr_df22 = afr_df['2022-01-01' :'2022-01-31']
afr_new_cases22 = afr_df22.groupby('month').agg(qty =('new_cases_per_million', 'sum')).astype({'qty':int})
afr_data = pd.concat([afr_new_cases21, afr_new_cases22], axis =0)
afr_data = afr_data.rename(columns = {'qty':'Africa'})

# Brazil:

bra_df21 = bra_df['2021-02-01' :'2021-12-31']
bra_new_cases21 = bra_df21.groupby('month').agg(qty =('new_cases_per_million', 'sum')).astype({'qty':int})
bra_df22 = bra_df['2022-01-01' :'2022-01-31']
bra_new_cases22 = bra_df22.groupby('month').agg(qty =('new_cases_per_million', 'sum')).astype({'qty':int})
bra_data = pd.concat([bra_new_cases21, bra_new_cases22], axis =0)
bra_data = bra_data.rename(columns = {'qty':'Brazil'})

# Now we concatenate all the individual data frames for each Country into one data frame called 'final_df'

final_df = pd.concat([rus_data, aus_data, ger_data, usa_data, new_data, sou_data, 
                      afr_data, jap_data, can_data, bra_data], axis = 1)


final_df.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)              # resetting the index.

final_df = final_df.transpose()                            # transposing the data frame.

# here we rename the indexes to represent months:

final_df.rename(columns = {0: 'Feb', 1: 'Mar', 2: 'Apr', 3: 'May', 4: 'Jun', 5: 'Jul', 
                           6: 'Aug', 7:'Sep', 8:'Oct', 9:'Nov', 10:'Dec', 11:'Jan'}, inplace=True)

plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))                                 # specify figure size.

# plot title:

plt.title('COVID-19 Cases Per Million For Each Country Per Month (February 2021 to January 2022)')

# plot heatmap with parameters and sorting values by 'Jan' in ascending order:

ax = sns.heatmap(final_df.sort_values(by=['Jan'], ascending=True), 
                 cmap="BuPu",robust = True, linewidth = 0.5, center = 8000)

plt.show()                                                  # show plot.

When looking at cases per million in each Country we see that in January 2022 Australia has experienced a proportionally larger amount of COVID-19 infections in the population compared to the other nations.

8. Over the last year, which months have been the most severe in terms of worldwide deaths?¶

In this visualisation we look at Global death numbers attributed to COVID-19 by aggregating monthly values and compare these totals as a percentage of the last 12 months via a Pie Chart:

In [10]:
# Ensuring the plot is displayed directly below the code cell that produced it:

%matplotlib inline

# libraries:

import pandas as pd                           # importing pandas library with structures and operations to manipulate data.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt               # setting style and plot attributes such as the range for x and y axes.

import seaborn as sns                         # importing seaborn for statistical data visualisation.

sns.set()                                     # turn on seaborn styling

# importing data as a panda data frame, filtering raw data with required columns and parsing dates:

dframe = pd.read_csv('owid-covid-data.csv', usecols=['location', 'date', 'new_deaths'], parse_dates=['date'])

# Splitting dates to create two new columns in the data frame:

dframe['year'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(dframe['date']).year           # creating a column for 'year'.

dframe['month'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(dframe['date']).month         # creating a column for 'month'.

dframe = dframe.set_index('date')                                # setting index to 'date'.

dframe = dframe.query('location == "World"')                     # using query to select values for 'World'.

dframe21 = dframe['2021-02-01' :'2021-12-31']                    # selecting date range for dates in 2021 only and assigning
                                                                 # these values to 'dframe21'.
    
# grouping data in 'dframe21' by month, summing values, and assigning these to 'dframe_new_21':
    
dframe_new_21 = dframe21.groupby('month').agg(qty =('new_deaths', 'sum')).astype({'qty':int})

dframe22 = dframe['2022-01-01' :'2022-01-31']                    # selecting date range for dates in 2022 (i.e. January)
                                                                 # and assigning these value to 'dframe22'.

# grouping data in 'dframe22' by month, summing values, and assigning these to 'dframe_new_22':

dframe_new_22 = dframe22.groupby('month').agg(qty =('new_deaths', 'sum')).astype({'qty':int})

# concatenating 'dframe_new_21' with 'dframe_new_22' and assigning to 'dframe_world' 
# to ensure correct order of monthly data:

dframe_world = pd.concat([dframe_new_21, dframe_new_22], axis =0)

# print(dframe_world) - this was used to check

df_list = dframe_world['qty'].tolist()                           # converting values in the data frame to a list
                                                                 # called 'df_list'.
# print(df_list) - this was used to check

colors = sns.color_palette("husl", 12)                           # define Seaborn color palette to use.

# creating a list called 'labels' so that the elemnts in the list can be used as labels in the pie chart:

labels = ['Feb 21', 'Mar 21', 'Apr 21', 'May 21', 'Jun 21', 'Jul 21', 'Aug 21', 'Sep 21', 
          'Oct 21', 'Nov 21', 'Dec 21','Jan 22']

plt.figure(figsize=(12,12))                                      # specify figure size.

plt.title('Percentage of Monthly Worldwide COVID-19 Deaths (February 2021 to January 2022)', fontsize = 15)

plt.pie(df_list, labels = labels, shadow = True, colors = colors, autopct='%.1f%%')  #create pie chart.

plt.show()                                                       # show plot.

From the pie chart we can see that over the last year, the months with the most global deaths due to COVID-19 were April 2021 and May 2021. Also, November 2021 has seen the lowest percentage of global deaths in the last 12 months.

9. Is there a correlation between specific variables in the data set?¶

In this example we produce a correlation matrix to visualise correlation between the total number of deaths, the total number of cases, the reproduction rate of the virus, the number of ICU patients, the total number of boosters administered, the availability of handwashing facilities, the number of hospital beds per thousand, and life expectancy:

In [11]:
# Ensuring the plot is displayed directly below the code cell that produced it:

%matplotlib inline

# libraries:

import pandas as pd                           # importing pandas library with structures and operations to manipulate data.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt               # setting style and plot attributes such as the range for x and y axes.

import seaborn as sns                         # importing seaborn for statistical data visualisation.

sns.set()                                     # turn on seaborn styling

# importing data as a panda data frame and filtering raw data with required columns:

df = pd.read_csv('owid-covid-data.csv',usecols=['total_deaths', 'total_cases','reproduction_rate',
 'icu_patients','total_boosters','handwashing_facilities',
 'hospital_beds_per_thousand',
 'life_expectancy'])

# using the spearman correlation coefficient from the scipy statistics library:

from scipy.stats import spearmanr 

# filtering the numeric columns (attributes) and using a for loop to iterate over all of the columns in the data
# so that if the item is numeric, its value will be stored in 'num_cols':

num_cols = [n for n,col in df.items() if pd.api.types.is_numeric_dtype(col)]

# obtaining the correlations between pairs within 'num_cols'. Here the dropna() function of Pandas Data Frame 
# drops all of the missing values:

corr = spearmanr(df[num_cols].dropna()).correlation

plt.figure(figsize=(16,12))       # specifying the figure size.

# setting the x and y labels since corr only holds the values in an array:

sns.heatmap(corr, annot=True, fmt='.2f', linewidths=.5,
          xticklabels = num_cols, yticklabels = num_cols); 

# setting title of plot:

plt.title(('Correlation Matrix for Chosen Variables in "The complete Our World in Data COVID-19 dataset"'),fontsize=15)   

# show plot:

plt.show()

From the correlation matrix we can see perfect correlation between the number of handwashing facilities and the number of hospital beds per thousand. We also see a very high correlation between handwashing facilities and life expectancy, as well as hospital beds per thousand and life expectancy. Additionally, there is a high negative correlation between handwashing facilities, hospital beds per thousand, and life expectancy paired against the total number of deaths.

10. How does the reproduction rate of the virus differ per Continent?¶

In this example we create a boxplot to visually assess the spread of the distribution of the reproduction rate across all the continents.

In [12]:
# Ensuring the plot is displayed directly below the code cell that produced it:

%matplotlib inline

# libraries:

import pandas as pd                           # importing pandas library with structures and operations to manipulate data.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt               # setting style and plot attributes such as the range for x and y axes.

import seaborn as sns                         # importing seaborn for statistical data visualisation.

sns.set()                                     # turn on seaborn styling.

# importing data as a panda data frame and filtering raw data with required columns:

df = pd.read_csv('owid-covid-data.csv',usecols=['continent','reproduction_rate'])

plt.figure(figsize=(18,6))                    # specifying the size of the plot.

# boxplot with parameters:
                                        
sns.boxplot(x = 'reproduction_rate', y = 'continent', data = df, palette = "RdYlGn", order = ["Africa","Oceania",
                                                                "Asia","North America","South America","Europe"])

# specifying the plot title and font size:

plt.title(('Distribution of Coronavirus Reproduction Rate Per Continent'),fontsize=19) 

plt.xlabel('Reproduction Rate', fontsize = 15);  # setting x-axis label.

plt.ylabel('');     # setting y-axis label to show nothing along the margin since continents are given.

plt.show()          # show plot

From the boxplot we can ascertain the spread of distributions of the Coronavirus reproduction rates per continent where the boxes themselves show the interquartile range. We can see that the median reproduction rate for Europe is the highest of the continents. We also see a large amount of outliers for each continent.

11. How does the reproduction rate of the virus differ per Continent? (Alternative visualisation)¶

In this visualisation we use violin plots to look at the same data as above. This allows for more insight:

In [13]:
# Ensuring the plot is displayed directly below the code cell that produced it:

%matplotlib inline

# libraries:

import pandas as pd                           # importing pandas library with structures and operations to manipulate data.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt               # setting style and plot attributes such as the range for x and y axes.

import seaborn as sns                         # importing seaborn for statistical data visualisation.

sns.set()                                     # turn on seaborn styling.

# importing data as a panda data frame and filtering raw data with required columns:

df = pd.read_csv('owid-covid-data.csv',usecols=['continent','reproduction_rate'])

plt.figure(figsize=(14,10))                    # specifying the size of the plot.

# specifying the plot title and font size:

plt.title(('Distribution of Coronavirus Reproduction Rate Per Continent'),fontsize=19) 

# violin plot just needs to know the columns you want represented and the data

sns.violinplot(x = 'reproduction_rate', y = 'continent', data = df, palette = "summer", scale = "width", order = ["Africa","Oceania",
                                                                "Asia","North America","South America","Europe"]); 

plt.xlabel('Reproduction Rate', fontsize = 15);  # setting x-axis label.

plt.ylabel('');     # setting y-axis label to show nothing along the margin since continents are given.

Violin plots allow for a more intuitive visualisation due to their characteristics which feature a kernel density estimation of the underlying distribution. It should be acknowledged though that the scale has been set to 'width' so each violin in this plot has the same width. This means that smaller samples appear proportionally larger. Nevertheless, the shape in each violin is indicative of the density for each distribution. For example, we can see Africa, Asia, and North America have greater density in their distributions towards a reproduction rate near zero.
